00:14:48.870 --> 00:14:50.870
were written more than 1,000 years

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:53.870
before the invention of what we know today as paper.

00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:56.870
The earliest Bible manuscripts were written

00:14:56.870 --> 00:14:59.870
on a material called papyrus.

00:14:59.870 --> 00:15:02.870
Papyrus is a plant that grows in shallow water

00:15:02.870 --> 00:15:05.870
with stalks that can reach almost 4.6 meters

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:07.870
or about 15 feet high.

00:15:07.870 --> 00:15:09.870
Over 4,000 years ago,

00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:12.870
the Egyptians invented ways to turn papyrus

00:15:12.870 --> 00:15:17.870
into a smooth, strong writing material similar to paper.

00:15:17.870 --> 00:15:19.870
Even with modern tools,

00:15:19.870 --> 00:15:22.870
you can see it was a lot of work.

00:15:22.870 --> 00:15:24.870
Thin slices of the plant's core

00:15:24.870 --> 00:15:27.870
had to be soaked and flattened,

00:15:27.870 --> 00:15:29.870
arranged in layers,

00:15:29.870 --> 00:15:34.179
and then beaten and pressed

00:15:34.179 --> 00:15:37.179
to bind the layers together.

00:15:37.179 --> 00:15:39.179
When the sheets were dry,

00:15:39.179 --> 00:15:41.179
they were polished with a piece of ivory,

00:15:41.179 --> 00:15:44.179
a smooth shell, or even a stone.

00:15:44.179 --> 00:15:48.179
The result was a relatively smooth surface for writing.

00:15:48.179 --> 00:15:50.179
To make a scroll,

00:15:50.179 --> 00:15:53.179
individual sheets of papyrus were pasted together along the edges,

00:15:53.179 --> 00:15:56.179
to make a roll that might be more than 6 meters

00:15:56.179 --> 00:15:58.179
or about 20 feet in length.

