00:16:12.100 --> 00:16:15.100
the papyrus pages were folded,

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:17.100
sewn, and bound together

00:16:17.100 --> 00:16:20.100
to form something similar to a modern book.

00:16:20.100 --> 00:16:22.100
Think of all the hours required

00:16:22.100 --> 00:16:25.100
to produce these materials to write on.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:27.100
But without modern pens and pencils,

00:16:27.100 --> 00:16:30.100
what did ancient people use to write with?

00:16:30.100 --> 00:16:33.419
The pens they used were often made

00:16:33.419 --> 00:16:36.419
from pieces of hard read like this.

00:16:36.419 --> 00:16:41.820
Carefully cut to produce a pointed slit.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:42.820
In Bible Times,

00:16:42.820 --> 00:16:44.820
one common type of ink that would be used

00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:46.820
with these read pens was made

00:16:46.820 --> 00:16:48.820
by combining blacksoot

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:50.820
with a rubbery gum

00:16:50.820 --> 00:16:52.820
that helped it stick to the page.

00:16:53.820 --> 00:16:55.820
Then water was added to the mixture.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:17:03.549
Whether in the form of a scroll or a codex,

00:17:03.549 --> 00:17:05.549
the problem with papyrus

00:17:05.549 --> 00:17:08.549
was that it decomposed easily.

00:17:08.549 --> 00:17:09.549
Amazingly,

00:17:09.549 --> 00:17:11.549
there are many fragments of Bible manuscripts

00:17:11.549 --> 00:17:15.549
on papyrus that have survived down to our day.

00:17:15.549 --> 00:17:17.549
What you see here are reproductions of fragments

00:17:17.549 --> 00:17:20.549
that are more than 2,000 years old.

00:17:20.549 --> 00:17:22.549
In time,

00:17:22.549 --> 00:17:23.549
Bible manuscripts began to be copied

00:17:23.549 --> 00:17:26.549
onto more durable materials.

00:17:26.549 --> 00:17:28.549
By about the 4th century,

00:17:28.549 --> 00:17:30.549
the most common of those was parchment.

00:17:30.549 --> 00:17:32.549
It was normally made from the hides of sheep,

00:17:32.549 --> 00:17:35.549
calves or goats.

00:17:35.549 --> 00:17:39.549
The process begins by soaking the hide and water in line,

00:17:39.549 --> 00:17:42.549
then removing the hair and excess flesh.

00:17:42.549 --> 00:17:48.829
After that,

00:17:48.829 --> 00:17:50.829
the skin is stretched on a frame

00:17:50.829 --> 00:17:51.829
and scraped with a knife

00:17:51.829 --> 00:17:54.829
to remove any residues like fat.

00:17:54.829 --> 00:17:56.829
The next step is to dry the skin

00:17:56.829 --> 00:17:58.829
under increased tension,

00:17:58.829 --> 00:18:00.829
which causes it to become stiff and flat.

00:18:02.829 --> 00:18:03.829
Finally,

00:18:03.829 --> 00:18:04.829
it's dusted with chalk

00:18:04.829 --> 00:18:06.829
and sanded smooth with pumice

00:18:06.829 --> 00:18:10.829
to create an even writing surface.

00:18:10.829 --> 00:18:11.829
As you can see,

00:18:11.829 --> 00:18:13.829
making even one sheet of parchment

00:18:13.829 --> 00:18:16.829
requires a tremendous amount of work.

00:18:16.829 --> 00:18:17.829
But today,

00:18:17.829 --> 00:18:18.829
there are many Bible manuscripts

00:18:18.829 --> 00:18:19.829
that were written on parchment,

00:18:19.829 --> 00:18:23.829
such as these two original manuscripts here.

00:18:23.829 --> 00:18:25.829
Another famous manuscript

00:18:25.829 --> 00:18:26.829
is the Codex Amiatinus

00:18:26.829 --> 00:18:27.829
located in Italy,

00:18:27.829 --> 00:18:30.829
which is over 1,300 years old.

00:18:30.829 --> 00:18:31.829
In fact,

00:18:31.829 --> 00:18:32.829
it's the oldest,

00:18:32.829 --> 00:18:33.829
complete Latin Bible

00:18:33.829 --> 00:18:36.829
bound in a single volume ever found.

00:18:36.829 --> 00:18:37.829
Some historians feel

00:18:37.829 --> 00:18:38.829
that it required the hides

00:18:38.829 --> 00:18:41.829
of over 400 animals to produce.

00:18:41.829 --> 00:18:45.460
This replica is big,

00:18:45.460 --> 00:18:47.460
but the original is even larger.

00:18:47.460 --> 00:18:49.460
It weighs 34 kilograms

00:18:49.460 --> 00:18:53.900
or about 75 pounds.

00:18:53.900 --> 00:18:54.900
Think of all of the work

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:55.900
that went into producing

00:18:55.900 --> 00:18:57.900
just that one Bible.

00:18:57.900 --> 00:18:59.900
Well, all of these materials

00:18:59.900 --> 00:19:00.900
are perishable

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:02.900
and deteriorate with time.

00:19:02.900 --> 00:19:04.900
But to preserve his word,

00:19:04.900 --> 00:19:05.900
Jehovah God sought to it

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:06.900
that the Bible was

00:19:06.900 --> 00:19:07.900
meticulously copied

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:09.900
and recopied over the centuries,

00:19:09.900 --> 00:19:10.900
so that today,

00:19:10.900 --> 00:19:11.900
we have not just a few,

00:19:11.900 --> 00:19:13.900
but thousands of manuscripts

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:16.900
of various parts of the Bible.

00:19:16.900 --> 00:19:17.900
So the next time you look

00:19:17.900 --> 00:19:18.900
up a Bible verse

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:19.900
by tapping on a link,

00:19:19.900 --> 00:19:21.900
think about what it took

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:23.900
to put those words in writing,

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:24.900
and how amazing it is

00:19:24.900 --> 00:19:25.900
that Jehovah's Word

00:19:25.900 --> 00:19:27.900
recorded using these ancient,

00:19:27.900 --> 00:19:28.900
fragile materials,

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:35.069
is still with us today.

00:19:35.069 --> 00:19:36.069
We're grateful

00:19:36.069 --> 00:19:38.069
to the countless God-fearing men

00:19:38.069 --> 00:19:40.069
who carefully wrote down

00:19:40.069 --> 00:19:42.069
and copied the Bible.

00:19:42.069 --> 00:19:44.069
Their hard work made it possible

00:19:44.069 --> 00:19:46.069
for us to have it today,

00:19:46.069 --> 00:19:47.069
thus fulfilling the words

00:19:47.069 --> 00:19:49.069
of the prophet Isaiah,

00:19:49.069 --> 00:19:51.069
the Word of our God,

00:19:51.069 --> 00:19:54.069
endures forever.

00:19:54.069 --> 00:19:55.069
Our great God, Jehovah,

00:19:55.069 --> 00:19:56.069
has used people

00:19:56.069 --> 00:19:58.069
from all walks of life

00:19:58.069 --> 00:20:00.069
to preserve his message

00:20:00.069 --> 00:20:02.069
and holy name.

00:20:02.069 --> 00:20:03.069
One such person

00:20:03.069 --> 00:20:05.069
was Benjamin Boothroyd,

00:20:05.069 --> 00:20:07.069
the son of a humble shoemaker,

00:20:07.069 --> 00:20:09.069
who became a minister

00:20:09.069 --> 00:20:11.069
and a printer.

00:20:11.069 --> 00:20:13.069
What caused this ordinary man

00:20:13.069 --> 00:20:16.069
to become a self-taught scholar

00:20:16.069 --> 00:20:18.069
and Bible translator?

00:20:18.069 --> 00:20:19.069
Let's find out.

00:20:19.069 --> 00:20:24.529
We sincerely congratulate

00:20:24.529 --> 00:20:27.529
Dr. B, on having completed a task

00:20:27.529 --> 00:20:29.529
that was perhaps never before

00:20:29.529 --> 00:20:32.529
accomplished by a single individual.

00:20:32.529 --> 00:20:35.529
Namely, a corrected Hebrew text

00:20:35.529 --> 00:20:37.529
of the Old Testament

00:20:37.529 --> 00:20:39.529
and a revised English version

00:20:39.529 --> 00:20:42.529
of the whole Bible.

00:20:42.529 --> 00:20:44.529
Benjamin Boothroyd was born

00:20:44.529 --> 00:20:48.529
in 1768 to a humble shoemaker.

00:20:48.529 --> 00:20:49.529
He lived his whole life

00:20:49.529 --> 00:20:51.529
in Yorkshire, England.

00:20:51.529 --> 00:20:53.529
Boothroyd wasn't wealthy

00:20:53.529 --> 00:20:55.529
or prominent,

00:20:55.529 --> 00:20:57.529
yet he accomplished something remarkable

00:20:57.529 --> 00:21:02.529
in the field of Bible translation.

00:21:02.529 --> 00:21:03.529
As a young man,

00:21:03.529 --> 00:21:05.529
Boothroyd and his friends

00:21:05.529 --> 00:21:07.529
would attend church

00:21:07.529 --> 00:21:09.529
and then go to a local ale house,

00:21:09.529 --> 00:21:13.529
not dissimilar to this one.

00:21:13.529 --> 00:21:15.529
It was on one of these occasions

00:21:15.529 --> 00:21:17.529
that Boothroyd experienced something

00:21:17.529 --> 00:21:19.529
that changed his life.

00:21:19.529 --> 00:21:21.529
The conversation was unusually

00:21:21.529 --> 00:21:23.529
profane and simple in which

00:21:23.529 --> 00:21:25.529
I joined and was perhaps

00:21:25.529 --> 00:21:28.529
worse than any of my companions.

00:21:28.529 --> 00:21:30.529
With a suddenness of almost a flash

00:21:30.529 --> 00:21:31.529
of lightning,

00:21:31.529 --> 00:21:33.529
my mind was struck with horror

00:21:33.529 --> 00:21:36.529
under a sense of my sin and guilt

00:21:36.529 --> 00:21:38.529
that I was a suitable victim

00:21:38.529 --> 00:21:42.529
for the miseries of hell.

00:21:42.529 --> 00:21:44.529
Without saying a word,

00:21:44.529 --> 00:21:46.529
Boothroyd left the ale house

00:21:46.529 --> 00:21:48.529
and his companions behind.

00:21:48.529 --> 00:21:53.630
As he walked home,

00:21:53.630 --> 00:21:55.630
he got down on his knees

00:21:55.630 --> 00:21:59.630
and begged God to have mercy on him.

00:21:59.630 --> 00:22:01.630
It was a pivotal moment.

00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:03.630
He resolved to dedicate

00:22:03.630 --> 00:22:06.630
the rest of his life to God.

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:10.329
We're here at the National Library of Wales

00:22:10.329 --> 00:22:12.329
to reveal the next chapter

00:22:12.329 --> 00:22:14.329
of Boothroyd's story.

00:22:14.329 --> 00:22:23.880
In 1801,

00:22:23.880 --> 00:22:25.880
Boothroyd married Sarah Hurst

00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:28.880
who shared his devotion and faith.

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:30.880
To supplement their income,

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:32.880
a couple ran a small bookshop

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:33.880
and printery.

00:22:33.880 --> 00:22:35.880
It was there

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:38.880
Boothroyd acquired these books.

00:22:38.880 --> 00:22:41.880
Lectures on the sacred poetry

00:22:41.880 --> 00:22:43.880
of the Hebrews.

00:22:43.880 --> 00:22:45.880
Those lectures on Hebrew

00:22:45.880 --> 00:22:47.880
poetry fell into my hands.

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:50.880
I read it with peculiar pleasure.

00:22:50.880 --> 00:22:52.880
Boothroyd fell in love

00:22:52.880 --> 00:22:54.880
with the Hebrew language.

00:22:54.880 --> 00:22:56.880
He decided to learn it.

00:22:56.880 --> 00:22:58.880
But how?

00:22:58.880 --> 00:22:59.880
Boothroyd noticed

00:22:59.880 --> 00:23:01.880
that some of the Psalms

00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:02.880
were split into standards

00:23:02.880 --> 00:23:05.880
using different Hebrew letters.

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:07.880
The names of the letters

00:23:07.880 --> 00:23:09.880
came from the 119th Psalm.

00:23:09.880 --> 00:23:11.880
And I began to read

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:13.880
the early part of the Pentateuch.

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:16.880
He painstakingly taught himself

00:23:16.880 --> 00:23:18.880
Hebrew letters,

00:23:18.880 --> 00:23:19.880
then words,

00:23:19.880 --> 00:23:20.880
then grammar,

00:23:20.880 --> 00:23:22.880
until he could read the Bible

00:23:22.880 --> 00:23:23.880
in Hebrew.

00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:27.259
On comparing the latest

00:23:27.259 --> 00:23:29.259
Hebrew printed texts,

00:23:29.259 --> 00:23:30.259
such as these

00:23:30.259 --> 00:23:32.259
by Benjamin Kenikot

00:23:32.259 --> 00:23:34.259
with older available manuscripts,

00:23:34.259 --> 00:23:35.259
Boothroyd discovered

00:23:35.259 --> 00:23:38.259
something troubling.

00:23:38.259 --> 00:23:41.259
It had many errors.

00:23:41.259 --> 00:23:42.259
This led him

00:23:42.259 --> 00:23:45.259
to a monumental decision.

00:23:45.259 --> 00:23:47.259
Boothroyd began a project

00:23:47.259 --> 00:23:49.259
to compile and publish

00:23:49.259 --> 00:23:51.259
a more accurate Hebrew text

00:23:51.259 --> 00:23:55.180
of the Old Testament.

00:23:55.180 --> 00:23:57.180
While he did the majority

00:23:57.180 --> 00:23:58.180
of the work,

00:23:58.180 --> 00:24:00.180
he wasn't alone.

00:24:00.180 --> 00:24:02.180
My wife learned the names

00:24:02.180 --> 00:24:03.180
of the Hebrew letters,

00:24:03.180 --> 00:24:05.180
and we examined the sheets,

00:24:05.180 --> 00:24:06.180
not by uttering words,

00:24:06.180 --> 00:24:08.180
but by pronouncing

00:24:08.180 --> 00:24:10.180
by letter.

00:24:10.180 --> 00:24:12.180
Sarah helped her husband

00:24:12.180 --> 00:24:13.180
proofread the work

00:24:13.180 --> 00:24:15.180
to confirm the accuracy.

00:24:15.180 --> 00:24:18.180
After years of meticulous work,

00:24:18.180 --> 00:24:21.180
they completed Boothroyd's

00:24:21.180 --> 00:24:22.180
Biblia Hebraica

00:24:22.180 --> 00:24:23.180
in two volumes

00:24:23.180 --> 00:24:25.180
in 1816.

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:27.180
Many would consider such

00:24:27.180 --> 00:24:28.180
an accomplishment

00:24:28.180 --> 00:24:29.180
to be the achievement

00:24:29.180 --> 00:24:31.180
of a lifetime.

00:24:31.180 --> 00:24:33.180
But Boothroyd

00:24:33.180 --> 00:24:34.180
was about to begin

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:37.180
another major undertaking.

00:24:38.180 --> 00:24:40.180
Boothroyd felt it was his duty

00:24:40.180 --> 00:24:42.180
to produce a revised Bible

00:24:42.180 --> 00:24:44.180
in plain English,

00:24:44.180 --> 00:24:46.180
a Bible that anyone

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:47.180
could understand.

00:24:47.180 --> 00:24:49.180
So, with the knowledge,

00:24:49.180 --> 00:24:50.180
materials, and means

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:51.180
available to him,

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:53.180
he went back to work.

00:24:53.180 --> 00:24:56.940
We're now at the University

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:57.940
in Lampeter

00:24:57.940 --> 00:24:59.940
to find out what Boothroyd accomplished.

00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:05.740
Just two years later,

00:25:05.740 --> 00:25:07.740
in 1818,

00:25:07.740 --> 00:25:09.740
he published the first volume

00:25:09.740 --> 00:25:11.740
of a new family Bible.

00:25:11.740 --> 00:25:13.740
The second volume was completed

00:25:13.740 --> 00:25:15.740
in 1821,

00:25:15.740 --> 00:25:17.740
and by 1824,

00:25:17.740 --> 00:25:19.740
the entire English translation

00:25:19.740 --> 00:25:21.740
was released.

00:25:21.740 --> 00:25:22.740
Once again,

00:25:22.740 --> 00:25:24.740
he hadn't accomplished this

00:25:24.740 --> 00:25:25.740
on his own.

00:25:25.740 --> 00:25:27.740
Through the whole of this important

00:25:27.740 --> 00:25:29.740
and laborious work,

00:25:29.740 --> 00:25:31.740
Mrs. Boothroyd was my

00:25:31.740 --> 00:25:33.740
chief support and assistant

00:25:33.740 --> 00:25:34.740
and to her,

00:25:34.740 --> 00:25:35.740
the public are as much

00:25:35.740 --> 00:25:37.740
indebted as myself.

00:25:37.740 --> 00:25:39.740
A new family Bible

00:25:39.740 --> 00:25:40.740
was appreciated

00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:42.740
by scholars and faithful

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:44.740
Bible readers alike.

00:25:44.740 --> 00:25:46.740
One thing in particular

00:25:46.740 --> 00:25:48.740
made Boothroyd's Bible

00:25:48.740 --> 00:25:50.740
especially significant.

00:25:50.740 --> 00:25:52.740
Boothroyd followed this rule

00:25:52.740 --> 00:25:53.740
while translating.

00:25:53.740 --> 00:25:55.740
I have adopted Chahova

00:25:55.740 --> 00:25:56.740
instead of Lord,

00:25:56.740 --> 00:25:57.740
and Chahova God

00:25:57.740 --> 00:25:59.740
is certainly more proper

00:25:59.740 --> 00:26:01.740
and just to the original

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:03.740
than Lord God.

00:26:03.740 --> 00:26:05.740
This was the first

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:07.740
English Bible ever published

00:26:07.740 --> 00:26:09.740
to consistently use Chahova

00:26:09.740 --> 00:26:11.740
in the Old Testament.

00:26:11.740 --> 00:26:13.740
Boothroyd also included

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:14.740
it several times

00:26:14.740 --> 00:26:16.740
in the New Testament.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:19.740
The University of Glasgow

00:26:19.740 --> 00:26:21.740
awarded Boothroyd a degree

00:26:21.740 --> 00:26:24.740
in recognition of this outstanding

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:26.740
piece of scholarship.

00:26:26.740 --> 00:26:28.740
His new family Bible was later

00:26:28.740 --> 00:26:30.740
used as the basis

00:26:30.740 --> 00:26:31.740
for translating the Bible

00:26:31.740 --> 00:26:32.740
into languages

00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:34.740
of the South Pacific,

00:26:34.740 --> 00:26:36.740
such as Tahisha.

00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:37.740
As a result,

00:26:37.740 --> 00:26:39.740
these two used Chahova's name

00:26:39.740 --> 00:26:41.740
extensively.

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:47.390
Using what was available to him,

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:49.390
Boothroyd peered

00:26:49.390 --> 00:26:51.390
into the Scriptures,

00:26:51.390 --> 00:26:53.390
seeking to know their meaning,

00:26:53.390 --> 00:26:55.390
and then worked to share

00:26:55.390 --> 00:26:57.390
that knowledge with others.

00:26:57.390 --> 00:26:59.390
In his dedication

00:26:59.390 --> 00:27:01.390
to his new family Bible,

00:27:01.390 --> 00:27:02.390
he wrote,

00:27:02.390 --> 00:27:07.410
I have no interest to serve

00:27:07.410 --> 00:27:09.410
but that of truth.

00:27:09.410 --> 00:27:11.410
This man

00:27:11.410 --> 00:27:13.410
of lowly origins

00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:15.410
achieved something truly rare.

00:27:15.410 --> 00:27:18.410
His works gave people knowledge

00:27:18.410 --> 00:27:19.410
of God's word,

00:27:19.410 --> 00:27:21.410
God's will,

00:27:21.410 --> 00:27:23.410
and God's name.

00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:29.789
How encouraging it was

00:27:29.789 --> 00:27:31.789
to see Boothroyd's efforts

00:27:31.789 --> 00:27:33.789
to help others understand God's word

00:27:33.789 --> 00:27:36.789
and to restore God's name

00:27:36.789 --> 00:27:40.519
to the English Bible.

00:27:40.519 --> 00:27:41.519
Through the Bible,

00:27:41.519 --> 00:27:43.519
Chahova also expresses his love

00:27:43.519 --> 00:27:44.519
for another group,

00:27:44.519 --> 00:27:46.519
Orphans.

00:27:46.519 --> 00:27:48.519
He wants these dear ones

00:27:48.519 --> 00:27:50.519
to feel especially cared for.

00:27:50.519 --> 00:27:52.519
Let's see how

00:27:52.519 --> 00:27:54.519
Nazar Kamar,

00:27:54.519 --> 00:27:56.519
a deaf man who was also

00:27:56.519 --> 00:27:58.519
an orphan,

00:27:58.519 --> 00:28:03.400
came to feel Chahova's love.

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:05.400
When I was a child,

00:28:05.400 --> 00:28:07.400
I attended a boarding school.

00:28:07.400 --> 00:28:09.400
All of my basic needs

00:28:09.400 --> 00:28:12.809
were taken care of.

00:28:12.809 --> 00:28:14.809
But on the weekends,

00:28:14.809 --> 00:28:16.809
I noticed that the other kids

00:28:16.809 --> 00:28:18.809
had parents that would take them home.

00:28:18.809 --> 00:28:20.809
No one ever came to take me home.

00:28:20.809 --> 00:28:24.309
They seemed so happy.

00:28:24.309 --> 00:28:28.170
I was alone.

00:28:28.170 --> 00:28:32.890
My name is Nazar Kamar.

00:28:32.890 --> 00:28:36.890
I was born in Kiev, Ukraine.

00:28:36.890 --> 00:28:38.890
And seven days after I was born,

00:28:38.890 --> 00:28:40.890
when I was still just a baby,

00:28:40.890 --> 00:28:44.890
my parents abandoned me.

00:28:44.890 --> 00:28:49.670
The school principal

00:28:49.670 --> 00:28:51.670
and teachers took turns caring for me.

00:28:51.670 --> 00:28:54.670
But I saw the other parents

00:28:54.670 --> 00:28:56.670
and how much they loved their children.

00:28:56.670 --> 00:29:00.670
I really wanted to have my own parents.

00:29:00.670 --> 00:29:02.670
I waited for them to come.

00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:04.670
But they never did.

00:29:04.670 --> 00:29:06.670
It was very painful.

00:29:06.670 --> 00:29:10.670
So I decided I needed a goal to focus on.

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:15.940
I hoped my parents were looking for me.

00:29:15.940 --> 00:29:17.940
And I thought playing sports

00:29:17.940 --> 00:29:19.940
might help them find me.

00:29:19.940 --> 00:29:21.940
They might see me

00:29:21.940 --> 00:29:23.940
and recognize that I am their son.

00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:25.940
I concentrated on getting good

00:29:25.940 --> 00:29:27.940
enough to play professionally.

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:29.940
I learned to play very well.

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:34.140
But my hope always was

00:29:34.140 --> 00:29:36.140
that when I traveled to different places,

00:29:36.140 --> 00:29:40.140
my parents might be sitting in the stands.

00:29:40.140 --> 00:29:42.140
And they would see me and say,

00:29:42.140 --> 00:29:44.140
this is our son.

00:29:44.140 --> 00:29:46.140
We found you.

00:29:46.140 --> 00:29:51.539
I began playing in a national league.

00:29:51.539 --> 00:29:55.539
And the team provided me a small room to live in

00:29:55.539 --> 00:29:59.539
and began to pay me a salary.

00:29:59.539 --> 00:30:01.539
It was not much.

00:30:01.539 --> 00:30:05.539
And not enough to live on.

00:30:05.539 --> 00:30:09.539
So I also got a job working at a factory.

00:30:09.539 --> 00:30:13.299
While working there, I met Sidge.

00:30:13.299 --> 00:30:18.670
He was one of Joe's witnesses.

00:30:18.670 --> 00:30:20.670
He would show me scriptures from the Bible,

00:30:20.670 --> 00:30:22.670
like Revelation 21, 3 and 4.

00:30:22.670 --> 00:30:24.670
About a future paradise

00:30:24.670 --> 00:30:26.670
with wonderful conditions

00:30:26.670 --> 00:30:28.670
where there would be no more suffering

00:30:28.670 --> 00:30:32.079
or pain.

00:30:32.079 --> 00:30:34.079
I wanted a life like that.

00:30:34.079 --> 00:30:38.079
But I didn't see those conditions around me.

00:30:38.079 --> 00:30:40.079
My life was very hard.

00:30:40.079 --> 00:30:44.079
So these promises were difficult to believe.

00:30:44.079 --> 00:30:47.460
Sidge also showed me God's name in the Bible

00:30:47.460 --> 00:30:49.460
at Exodus 15-3.

00:30:49.460 --> 00:30:53.460
And he explained to me the meaning of God's name, Jehovah.

00:30:53.460 --> 00:30:57.460
That he can become whatever he chooses to become.

00:30:57.460 --> 00:30:59.460
When I connected that name

00:30:59.460 --> 00:31:03.460
with his promise at Revelation 21, 3 and 4,

00:31:03.460 --> 00:31:05.460
it was then that I started to believe it.

00:31:05.460 --> 00:31:10.240
At my first meeting,

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:12.240
I was amazed by what I saw.

00:31:12.240 --> 00:31:16.240
The hearing and the deaf were communicating together.

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:18.240
They had unity,

00:31:18.240 --> 00:31:20.240
and they cared for each other.

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:22.240
I felt comfortable there.

00:31:22.240 --> 00:31:25.549
At one of the meetings,

00:31:25.549 --> 00:31:27.549
I saw the verse at Psalm 68-5,

00:31:27.549 --> 00:31:29.549
which refers to Jehovah God

00:31:29.549 --> 00:31:31.549
as the Father of the Fatherless.

00:31:31.549 --> 00:31:33.549
I was touched.

00:31:33.549 --> 00:31:37.549
He knows exactly how hard it is to be an orphan.

00:31:37.549 --> 00:31:39.549
He fully understands me.

00:31:39.549 --> 00:31:41.549
It gave me goose bumps.

00:31:41.549 --> 00:31:43.549
And I felt an inner peace and comfort.

00:31:43.549 --> 00:31:48.859
When my basketball team and the deaf community

00:31:48.859 --> 00:31:52.859
learned that I was studying the Bible with Jehovah's Witnesses,

00:31:52.859 --> 00:31:56.240
they were very upset with me.

00:31:56.240 --> 00:31:58.240
They told me I would lose their support.

00:31:58.240 --> 00:32:04.509
I would lose my salary and housing.

00:32:04.509 --> 00:32:06.509
I was at a crossroads.

00:32:06.509 --> 00:32:08.509
Since I'm an orphan,

00:32:08.509 --> 00:32:10.509
where would I live?

00:32:10.509 --> 00:32:12.509
This was a very difficult time.

00:32:12.509 --> 00:32:18.910
I noticed that I didn't feel the same unity

00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:20.910
or connection with my team,

00:32:20.910 --> 00:32:24.910
as I did with Jehovah's Witnesses.

00:32:24.910 --> 00:32:28.910
So, I decided to continue to study the Bible.

00:32:28.910 --> 00:32:32.740
I gave up their support.

00:32:32.740 --> 00:32:34.740
And God baptized.

00:32:34.740 --> 00:32:38.750
Jehovah has blessed me.

00:32:38.750 --> 00:32:40.750
I am no longer alone.

00:32:40.750 --> 00:32:42.750
I have my own family now.

00:32:42.750 --> 00:32:44.750
My wife, yet the Kia.

00:32:44.750 --> 00:32:48.750
We love and cherish each other so much.

00:32:48.750 --> 00:32:52.859
He has also given me brothers and sisters

00:32:52.859 --> 00:32:54.859
who care about me.

00:32:54.859 --> 00:32:58.859
They are my spiritual family.

00:32:58.859 --> 00:33:02.859
My life is no longer full of pain.

00:33:02.859 --> 00:33:04.859
Today, I still search for my parents

00:33:04.859 --> 00:33:06.859
and wait for them.

00:33:06.859 --> 00:33:08.859
Because when I find them,

00:33:08.859 --> 00:33:10.859
I want to help them

00:33:10.859 --> 00:33:12.859
by telling them about God's name.

00:33:12.859 --> 00:33:16.859
Now, I no longer consider myself an orphan,

00:33:16.859 --> 00:33:18.859
because I have a father.

00:33:18.859 --> 00:33:20.859
My father in heaven,

00:33:20.859 --> 00:33:22.859
whose name is Jehovah.

00:33:22.859 --> 00:33:24.859
When we search for love and acceptance

00:33:24.859 --> 00:33:30.059
in the congregation,

00:33:30.059 --> 00:33:34.059
we'll find that we belong to a caring family.

00:33:34.059 --> 00:33:38.059
Lovers of truth have sacrificed

00:33:38.059 --> 00:33:40.059
more than time and energy.

00:33:40.059 --> 00:33:42.059
Many of sacrifice their very lives

00:33:42.059 --> 00:33:44.059
so that we can have God's word

00:33:44.059 --> 00:33:46.059
in a language we understand.

00:33:46.059 --> 00:33:50.059
Let's visit the Belgium Bethel Bible Museum

00:33:50.059 --> 00:33:54.059
to learn who took such a risk and why.

00:33:54.059 --> 00:34:03.539
Jehovah gave us the Bible

00:34:03.539 --> 00:34:05.539
so that we could know Him

00:34:05.539 --> 00:34:07.539
and love Him.

00:34:07.539 --> 00:34:11.539
He wants us to become His friends.

00:34:11.539 --> 00:34:16.980
Jehovah made sure that the Bible

00:34:16.980 --> 00:34:18.980
would be available

00:34:18.980 --> 00:34:20.980
no matter where people live

00:34:20.980 --> 00:34:22.980
or what language they speak.

00:34:22.980 --> 00:34:26.699
The Bible Museum,

00:34:26.699 --> 00:34:28.699
located at the branch office

00:34:28.699 --> 00:34:30.699
of Jehovah's Witnesses in Brussels, Belgium,

00:34:30.699 --> 00:34:32.699
with the theme,

00:34:32.699 --> 00:34:34.699
the Bible and the low countries,

00:34:34.699 --> 00:34:36.699
tells the fascinating story

00:34:36.699 --> 00:34:38.699
of Bible translation and production

00:34:38.699 --> 00:34:40.699
in the coastal region

00:34:40.699 --> 00:34:42.699
of Northwestern Europe.

00:34:42.699 --> 00:34:44.699
In this museum,

00:34:44.699 --> 00:34:46.699
you will learn of honest hearted people

00:34:46.699 --> 00:34:48.699
who came to love the Bible

00:34:48.699 --> 00:34:50.699
and wanted to make it available to others.

00:34:50.699 --> 00:34:57.599
Throughout the Middle Ages,

00:34:57.599 --> 00:34:59.599
the Roman Catholic Church

00:34:59.599 --> 00:35:01.599
feared the spread of Bibles

00:35:01.599 --> 00:35:03.599
in vernacular languages.

00:35:03.599 --> 00:35:05.599
Understanding the Bible

00:35:05.599 --> 00:35:07.599
would have exposed the

00:35:07.599 --> 00:35:09.599
unchristian behavior of the Church.

00:35:09.599 --> 00:35:13.599
This led to cruel persecution

00:35:13.599 --> 00:35:15.599
of Bible translators.

00:35:15.599 --> 00:35:17.599
What role did the region

00:35:17.599 --> 00:35:19.599
of the low countries play

00:35:19.599 --> 00:35:23.599
in this overheated religious atmosphere?

00:35:23.599 --> 00:35:25.599
By the 16th century,

00:35:25.599 --> 00:35:27.599
the city of Antwerp, Belgium,

00:35:27.599 --> 00:35:29.599
had become the leading

00:35:29.599 --> 00:35:31.599
commercial center of Western Europe.

00:35:31.599 --> 00:35:33.599
Antwerp's relatively tolerant

00:35:33.599 --> 00:35:35.599
religious and political climate

00:35:35.599 --> 00:35:37.599
made it an ideal hub

00:35:37.599 --> 00:35:39.599
for translating and printing Bibles

00:35:39.599 --> 00:35:41.599
in common everyday languages.

00:35:41.599 --> 00:35:43.599
About 270 printers,

00:35:43.599 --> 00:35:45.599
publishers and booksellers

00:35:45.599 --> 00:35:47.599
were located in this cosmopolitan city.

00:35:47.599 --> 00:35:49.599
In addition,

00:35:49.599 --> 00:35:51.599
the significant seaport

00:35:51.599 --> 00:35:53.599
was perfect for smuggling Bibles

00:35:53.599 --> 00:35:55.599
to neighboring countries.

00:35:55.599 --> 00:35:57.599
One of the many printers

00:35:57.599 --> 00:35:59.599
working in Antwerp

00:35:59.599 --> 00:36:01.599
was Jakub van Lee's belt.

00:36:01.599 --> 00:36:03.599
In 1526,

00:36:03.599 --> 00:36:05.599
he courageously published

00:36:05.599 --> 00:36:07.599
the first complete Bible in Dutch.

00:36:07.599 --> 00:36:09.599
This was one of the first Bibles

00:36:09.599 --> 00:36:11.599
printed in a single volume.

00:36:11.599 --> 00:36:13.599
Van Lee's belt eventually printed

00:36:13.599 --> 00:36:15.599
a total of 19 Bible editions.

00:36:15.599 --> 00:36:19.599
Despite the comparatively safe working conditions

00:36:19.599 --> 00:36:21.599
in Antwerp, Bible publishers

00:36:21.599 --> 00:36:23.599
were not fully protected from the church.

00:36:23.599 --> 00:36:27.599
Van Lee's belt was condemned to death

00:36:27.599 --> 00:36:29.599
for including marginal notes

00:36:29.599 --> 00:36:31.599
in his final edition of the Dutch Bible.

00:36:31.599 --> 00:36:33.599
Notes which the Catholic Church

00:36:33.599 --> 00:36:35.599
found offensive to their dogma.

00:36:35.599 --> 00:36:37.599
He was one of several

00:36:37.599 --> 00:36:39.599
Antwerp Bible printers

00:36:39.599 --> 00:36:41.599
executed for their work.

00:36:41.599 --> 00:36:43.599
A translator

00:36:43.599 --> 00:36:45.599
who also published his work in Antwerp

00:36:45.599 --> 00:36:47.599
was the French scholar

00:36:47.599 --> 00:36:49.599
Jacques Lafevre de Tape.

00:36:49.599 --> 00:36:51.599
He dedicated himself

00:36:51.599 --> 00:36:53.599
to restoring the original meaning

00:36:53.599 --> 00:36:55.599
of ancient writings

00:36:55.599 --> 00:36:57.599
and studied closely

00:36:57.599 --> 00:36:59.599
the Latin Volgate Bible.

00:36:59.599 --> 00:37:01.599
He strongly believed

00:37:01.599 --> 00:37:03.599
in the right

00:37:03.599 --> 00:37:05.599
of every Christian

00:37:05.599 --> 00:37:07.599
to read and learn the Bible personally.

00:37:07.599 --> 00:37:09.599
Therefore,

00:37:09.599 --> 00:37:11.599
the Fevre devoted all his energy

00:37:11.599 --> 00:37:13.599
to translating the Bible into French.

00:37:13.599 --> 00:37:15.599
It was the first

00:37:15.599 --> 00:37:17.599
complete Bible to be printed

00:37:17.599 --> 00:37:19.599
in this language.

00:37:19.599 --> 00:37:21.599
He was sure

00:37:21.599 --> 00:37:23.599
the Gospels would be, as he said,

00:37:23.599 --> 00:37:25.599
purely proclaimed

00:37:25.599 --> 00:37:27.599
throughout the world

00:37:27.599 --> 00:37:29.599
so that people may no longer be

00:37:29.599 --> 00:37:31.599
led astray by alien doctrines of men.

00:37:31.599 --> 00:37:33.599
Although his Bible translation

00:37:33.599 --> 00:37:35.599
initially was approved

00:37:35.599 --> 00:37:37.599
by the Holy Roman Emperor

00:37:37.599 --> 00:37:39.599
Charles V. In 1546,

00:37:39.599 --> 00:37:41.599
the Fevre's second edition

00:37:41.599 --> 00:37:43.599
was placed on the

00:37:43.599 --> 00:37:45.599
Roman Catholic Church's

00:37:45.599 --> 00:37:47.599
index of forbidden books.

00:37:47.599 --> 00:37:49.599
Another courageous man,

00:37:49.599 --> 00:37:51.599
one who translated the scriptures

00:37:51.599 --> 00:37:53.599
into English, was a clergyman

00:37:53.599 --> 00:37:55.599
and a scholar of Greek

00:37:55.599 --> 00:37:57.599
and Latin.

00:37:57.599 --> 00:37:59.599
The name of this man was

00:37:59.599 --> 00:38:01.599
William Tindale.

00:38:01.599 --> 00:38:03.599
He was passionate about God's word.

00:38:03.599 --> 00:38:05.599
Tindale wrote,

00:38:05.599 --> 00:38:07.599
we must desire God

00:38:07.599 --> 00:38:09.599
to make us understand

00:38:09.599 --> 00:38:11.599
and feel

00:38:11.599 --> 00:38:13.599
wherefor the scripture was given.

00:38:13.599 --> 00:38:15.599
That we may apply the medicine

00:38:15.599 --> 00:38:17.599
of the scripture.

00:38:17.599 --> 00:38:19.599
For translating the new testament

00:38:19.599 --> 00:38:21.599
into English, he was chased

00:38:21.599 --> 00:38:23.599
and hunted by church and state.

00:38:23.599 --> 00:38:25.599
He sought refuge in various cities

00:38:25.599 --> 00:38:27.599
including the city of Antwerp.

00:38:27.599 --> 00:38:29.599
Here,

00:38:29.599 --> 00:38:31.599
he published a revised version

00:38:31.599 --> 00:38:33.599
of the new testament

00:38:33.599 --> 00:38:35.599
and his translation

00:38:35.599 --> 00:38:37.599
of the Pentateuch

00:38:37.599 --> 00:38:39.599
where he used Jehovah's name

00:38:39.599 --> 00:38:41.599
for the first time

00:38:41.599 --> 00:38:43.599
in an English translation.

00:38:43.599 --> 00:38:45.599
Tindale also was executed

00:38:45.599 --> 00:38:47.599
for his translation work.

00:38:47.599 --> 00:38:49.599
Publishing Bibles

00:38:49.599 --> 00:38:51.599
in Spain was a very

00:38:51.599 --> 00:38:53.599
dangerous undertaking.

00:38:53.599 --> 00:38:55.599
For this reason,

00:38:55.599 --> 00:38:57.599
in 1543, the translator

00:38:57.599 --> 00:38:59.599
Francisco Danthenus

00:38:59.599 --> 00:39:01.599
also printed in Antwerp.

00:39:01.599 --> 00:39:03.599
It was the first

00:39:03.599 --> 00:39:05.599
Spanish version to be translated

00:39:05.599 --> 00:39:07.599
directly from the original

00:39:07.599 --> 00:39:09.599
Greek text.

00:39:09.599 --> 00:39:11.599
He wrote,

00:39:11.599 --> 00:39:13.599
it seemed to me that I had

00:39:13.599 --> 00:39:15.599
but one task.

00:39:15.599 --> 00:39:17.599
To commit to the press,

00:39:17.599 --> 00:39:19.599
the work I had taken

00:39:19.599 --> 00:39:21.599
pains to produce.

00:39:21.599 --> 00:39:23.599
And then commended to God,

00:39:23.599 --> 00:39:27.519
the father of the whole business

00:39:27.519 --> 00:39:29.519
for whose cause it had been made.

00:39:29.519 --> 00:39:31.519
So arrested for his work.

00:39:31.519 --> 00:39:33.519
Yet, some copies of his

00:39:33.519 --> 00:39:35.519
new testament made it to Spain.

00:39:35.519 --> 00:39:37.519
It had a strong influence

00:39:37.519 --> 00:39:39.519
on other Spanish translations

00:39:39.519 --> 00:39:41.519
such as the widely

00:39:41.519 --> 00:39:43.519
known Reina Valera Bible.

00:39:43.519 --> 00:39:45.519
The first edition of which

00:39:45.519 --> 00:39:47.519
was also printed in the low countries.

00:39:47.519 --> 00:39:50.960
There are many more

00:39:50.960 --> 00:39:52.960
intriguing gems for you

00:39:52.960 --> 00:39:54.960
to discover in this museum.

00:39:54.960 --> 00:39:56.960
Like the Antwerp Polyglot,

00:39:56.960 --> 00:39:58.960
which contains Bible text

00:39:58.960 --> 00:40:00.960
of five languages.

00:40:00.960 --> 00:40:02.960
And the secretly produced

00:40:02.960 --> 00:40:04.960
Dutch Jehovah Bible.

00:40:04.960 --> 00:40:06.960
All printed

00:40:06.960 --> 00:40:11.389
in the low countries.

00:40:11.389 --> 00:40:13.389
All these men displayed

00:40:13.389 --> 00:40:15.389
love for God's word.

00:40:15.389 --> 00:40:17.389
And Jehovah blessed their efforts

